The DAG itself is not seed-driven. The seed affects node selection in some paths and generator selection, but the DAG build is a deterministic dependency pass over the already chosen generators.

The flow has three separate stages:

Chain node selection
In app_backend.py:13017, _pick_flag_chain_nodes(...) does not use round robin. It is a heuristic:
It finds eligible nodes first: vuln nodes, plus non-vuln Docker nodes if flag-node-generators are enabled.
If one connected component already has enough eligible nodes, it picks from the largest component.
Otherwise it approximates graph diameter with two BFS passes, takes eligible nodes along that path, then falls back to a BFS walk, then fills from remaining eligible nodes.
After that it shuffles the final order.
So this part is “graph heuristic + shuffle”, not greedy optimization and not round robin.

There is a separate duplicate-allowed variant in app_backend.py:13172, _pick_flag_chain_nodes_allow_duplicates(...), and that one does use                                                      a seed when it has to extend the chain with repeated nodes.

Generator assignment
In app_backend.py:16387, _flow_compute_flag_assignments(...) is where the flow seed matters most.
The seed comes from app_backend.py:15341, _get_flow_seed(...), with priority:
explicit override
preview.flow_seed
preview.seed
0
Then assignment works like this:

It builds a candidate pool per chain position based on node type:
vuln nodes can take flag-generator
non-vuln Docker nodes can take flag-node-generator
It tracks “known facts” / artifacts produced so far.
If goal_facts exist, it tries a DFS/backtracking search first to find a solvable sequence.
Otherwise it does a greedy-ish step-by-step selection:
filter candidates whose requirements are already satisfied
score them by how many new facts they produce, with extra weight for goal facts
choose among scored candidates using seeded randomness
So this stage is best described as “constraint-filtered, score-based selection with seeded weighted randomness”, plus optional DFS when goal facts are present.

DAG reorder
After chain nodes and generators are already chosen, app_backend.py:18388, _flow_reorder_chain_by_generator_dag(...), may reorder the chain for non-preset auto-generated flows.
That function calls dag.py:94, build_dag(...). The DAG builder:

computes required artifacts from instance requires plus plugin requires
computes produced artifacts from plugin produces
adds an edge from every compatible producer to every consumer
honors explicit source bindings if present
treats “initial artifacts” as pre-existing inputs
Important point: it does not pick one producer greedily. It connects all valid producers for each required artifact.

Then it topologically sorts the resulting graph using Kahn’s algorithm in dag.py:234:

start with nodes that have zero incoming edges
process them in sorted order
remove outgoing edges
append newly ready nodes, again sorted
So when multiple orderings are valid, tie-breaking is lexical by challenge id, not seeded randomness.

What that means in practice:

The seed influences which nodes get chosen and which generators get assigned.
The DAG does not use the seed.
The DAG reorder is dependency-driven and deterministic for a given set of chosen generators.
It is not round robin.
It is not a greedy “pick nearest dependency” algorithm.
It is “build full artifact dependency graph, then topologically sort”.
One more nuance: presets and saved chains mostly bypass DAG reordering. In app_backend.py:19154, the reorder is only applied for auto-generated, non-preset, non-duplicate chains. Presets keep their intended order.

